'''Emily Nasrallah''' Imil<U+012B> Na<U+1E63>r All<U+0101>h <U+0627><U+0645><U+064A><U+0644><U+064A> <U+0646><U+0635><U+0631><U+0627><U+0644><U+0644><U+0647> ''[[n<U+00E9>e]]'' Emily Abi Rashed on July 6 1931 in [[Kfeir]], [[Lebanon]]) is a Lebanese writer and women's rights activist,.<ref name="biog">http://www.emilynasrallah.com/english/biography.html</ref>. She graduated from the Beirut University College (now the [[Lebanese American University]]) and the [[American University of Beirut]] in 1958 with a degree in Education. As well as journalistic articles, Nasrallah is the author of several novels.<ref name="publications">http://www.emilynasrallah.com/english/books/novels.html</ref>


==Early life==
Emily Abi Rashed was born in small village of al-Kfayr at the western foot of [[Mount Hermon]] in southern [[Lebanon]] on 6 July 1931,. She received her formal education in the elementary public school of al-Kfayr.<ref name="biog"/> Emily left her native town when she was only nine years of age, she wanted to go after her  brother who was sent to be schooled away from al-Kfayr. Emily wrote to an uncle of hers who had emigrated to [[West Virginia]], he granted her wish and payed for her tuition at [[Choueifat]] National College _a boarding school in the suburbs of [[Beirut]]_  where she continued her secondary  education. Emily taught for two years at the Choueifat school after attending there as a student, she continued her education at the[[Lebanese American University |Beirut College for Women]]<ref name="MC">{{Cite book | edition = illustrated | publisher = Cambridge University Press | isbn = 9780521341929 | volume = Issue 14 of Cambridge Middle East library | pages = 208 | last = Cooke | first = Miriam | title = War's other voices: women writers on the Lebanese civil war | series = Landmarks of World Literature | accessdate = 2009-11-19 | date = 1988 | url = http://books.google.com/books?id=5NJfRNeS1EYC&pg=PA144&dq=Emily+nasrallah&as_brr=3&ei=U5UFS-SVLaO8zgS60eGXDg#v=onepage&q=Emily%20nasrallah&f=false }}</ref> before majoring with a BE in education and literature from the [[American University of Beirut]] in 1958.<ref name="JZ">{{Cite book | publisher = SUNY Press | isbn = 9780791421710 | pages = 363 | last = Zeidan | first = Joseph T. | title = Arab women novelists: the formative years and beyond | series = SUNY series in Middle Eastern Studies | accessdate = 2009-11-19 | date = 1995 | url = http://books.google.com/books?id=J6YXo4VV6yMC&pg=PA119&dq=Emily+nasrallah&ei=2JMFS4rvOKaQyATazujaDg#v=onepage&q=Emily%20nasrallah&f=false }}</ref> After graduation, Emily taught at the [[Ahliah school]] in Beirut where [[Hanan al-Shaykh]] had been a pupil.<ref name="MC"/> Emily had also contributed, while still a student and during her teaching career to Lebanese periodicals and journals such as ''as-Sayyad'' (the hunter) and ''Sawt al-Mar'a'' (The voice of Women), sometimes using a pen name.<ref name="JZ"/><ref name="MC"/>  

Emily married Philip Nasrallah, a [[chemist]] from [[Zahleh]] in 1957 while still in college. The couple had four children: Ramzi, Maha, Khalil, and Mona.<ref name="JZ"/>
 
==Works==
===Novels===
* ''Tuyur Aylul'' (The birds of September) was Nasrallah's first novel it received critical acclaim and  three Arabic literary prizes within the same year of publication in 1962; the prizes are: Laureate Best Novel, the [[Said Akl]] Prize, and Friends of the Book Prize.

* ''Shajarat al-Difla'' (The olenader tree), published in 1968.
* ''al-Rahina'' (The hostage), 1974
* ''Tilka l-dhikrayat'' (Those memories), 1980
* ''al-Iqla<U+02BF> <U+02BF>aks al-zaman'' (Flight against time), 1981
* ''al-Jamr al-ghafi'' (The sleeping amber), 1995<ref name="MLT">{{Cite book | publisher = American university in Cairo press | isbn = 9789774161469 | pages = 526 | last = Ashour | first = Radwa | coauthors = Ferial Ghazoul, Hasna Reda Mekdashi, Mandy McClure | title = Arab Women Writers: A Critical Reference Guide, 1873-1999 | series = Arab Women Writers | date = 2008 }}</ref> 
* ''Ma Hadatha Fi Jouzour Tamaya'' (What Happened in the Tamaya Islands) 					

===Short Stories===
* ''Jazirat al-Wahm'' (The island of illusion), 1973 
* ''al-Yanbou<U+02BF> '' (The Spring), 1978
* ''al-Mar'a fi 17 qissa'' (Women in 17 stories), 1984
* ''al-Tahuna al-da'i<U+02BF>a'' (The lost mill), 1984
* '' Khubzuna al-yami'' (Our daily bread), 1988
* ''Mahattat al-rahil'' (Stations on a jouney), 1996<ref name="MLT"/>
* ''Rawat lia al-ayyam'' (Days recounted), 1997
* ''Al-Layali al-Ghajariyya'' (Gypsy Nights), 1998
* ''Awraq Minsiah'' (Forgotten papers)
* ''Aswad wa Abyiad''  (Black and White)
* ''Riyah janoubiyyah'' (Southern Winds)


===Children's literature===
* ''Shadi as-Saghi'' (Little Shadi), 1977
* ''al-Bahira'' (The Resplendent Flower)
* ''Mudhakkirat qitta'' (A cat's diary), 1988
* ''Ala Bissat al Thalj'' (On a Snow Carpet)
* ''Al Ghazala'' (The Gazelle)
* ''Anda al Khawta'' (Anda the Fool)
* ''Ayna tathhab Anda?'' (Where does Anda go?)<ref name="MLT"/>

===Non fiction===
* ''Nisaa' Raidat'' - Volumes 1,2 and 3 Biographies of pioneer women From the East
* ''Nisaa' Raidat'' - Volumes 4,5 and 6 Biographies of pioneer women From the West
* ''Fil Bal" (Recollections of start-up of Journalistic Career)

